'''Santō Kyōzan''' (山東 京山, June 15, 1769 (Meiwa 6) – October 30, 1858 (Ansei 5, 24th day of the 9th month)) was a late Edo period {{ill|gesaku writer|ja|戯作者|12=draft|12=draft}}. His real name was Iwase Momoki (岩瀬 百樹), and his courtesy name was Tetsubai. He also used the pen names Ranzan and Ryōsen. He was the younger brother of {{ill|Santō Kyōden|ja|山東京伝|12=draft|12=draft}}. [[File:(Kagamiyama) zori-hachi no dan (BM 1998,0218,0.22).jpg|thumb|200px|Flowery Cats Play, ''Kagamiyama Zōri Hachi no Dan'' by Santō Kyōzan (text) and [[Utagawa Kuniyoshi]] (art)]]
== Biography == Santō Kyōzan was born as the second son of a pawnbroker in {{ill|Fukagawa|ja|深川 (江東区)|12=draft|12=draft}}, Edo.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Santō Kyōden｜National Histories Dictionary・Japanese Language Dictionary・Comprehensive Japanese Encyclopedia・World Encyclopedia｜JapanKnowledge |url=https://japanknowledge.com/introduction/keyword.html?i=398 |website=JapanKnowledge |access-date=2023-09-23 |first=NetAdvance Inc. |last=Inc.}}</ref> As a child, he studied classical Chinese literature, calligraphy, and painting. In 1791 (Kansei 3), he became the adopted son of his aunt, the wife of the {{ill|Inukai family|ja|猪飼氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, and entered the service of the Sasayama Domain, but he retired eight years later.<ref>{{Cite book|和書 |author=Mayumi Tsuda |title=Santō Kyōzan Nenpukō |publisher=Perikan Publishing |year=2006 |pages=16, 23 |isbn=4831510661}}</ref> After two failed marriages, he settled in {{ill|Kyōbashi|ja|京橋 (東京都中央区)|12=draft|12=draft}}, making a living through {{ill|tenkoku|ja|篆刻|12=draft|12=draft}} (seal carving) and writing {{ill|gōkan|ja|合巻|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|yomihon|ja|読本|12=draft|12=draft}}.
[[File:(Michiyuki) nekoyanagi sakari no tsukikage (BM 1998,0218,0.21).jpg|thumb|200px|Flowery Cats Play, ''Michiyuki Nekoyanagi no Tsukikage'' by Santō Kyōzan (text) and Utagawa Kuniyoshi (art)]] [[File:Hokuetsu Se11u Part 2 volume 1.jpg|thumb|160px|''{{ill|Hokuetsu Se11u|ja|北越雪譜|12=draft|12=draft}}'' Volume Two, written by {{ill|Suzuki Bokushi|ja|鈴木牧之|12=draft|12=draft}}, published in Tenpō 12 (1841)]]
Santō Kyōzan's representative works include ''Fukushū Imoseyama Monogatari'' (''The Tale of Vengeance at Imoseyama,'' 1807) and ''Mukashi Moyō Musume Hyōbanki'' (''Old Patterns of Maidenly Fame,'' 1835).<ref>{{kotobank|Mukashi Moyō Musume Hyōbanki|デジタル大辞泉の解説}}</ref><ref>Takagi Gen (trans.), illustrated by {{ill|Utagawa Kunisada|ja|歌川国貞|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Utagawa Kunisada III|ja|歌川国貞 (3代目)|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Utagawa Kuniteru II|ja|歌川国輝 (2代目)|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Utagawa Yoshitsuna|ja|歌川芳綱|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Utagawa Kuniyoshi}}. ''Santō Kyōzan: Tales of Eccentric Antiquity'' (Edo Strange Tales and Curiosities Anthology). 2003. ISBN: 978-4336042743.</ref> His lifelong projects include ''Ōmisoka Akebono Zōshi'' (''New Year's Eve Dawn Tales,'' begun in Tenpō 10 (1839)) and ''Oborozuki Neko Kusazōshi'' (''Oborozuki's Cat Tales,'' 1842–1849), illustrated by Utagawa Kuniyoshi.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Oborozuki Neko Kusazōshi Vol. 7, 28 volumes|NCID=BB04697476|12=draft}}. In 2013, translated and republished as ''The Great Adventures of Okoma: Tales of Oborozuki’s Cat'' by Kaneko Nobuhisa. ISBN: 978-4756244291.</ref> He also wrote ''Kyōkusō Nyōbō Kageki'' (''Female Models for Moral Instruction,'' Kōka 3 (1846)), which incorporated moral lessons targeted at women and girls. His essay ''Rekisei Jōsōkō'' (''An Examination of Female Dress Across the Ages,'' Kōka 4 (1847)) remains a valuable historical source on Edo-period customs.
[[File:SantoKyozan20111123.jpg|thumb|200px|Grave of Santō Kyōzan]] He also contributed to the publication of Suzuki Bokushi's ''Hokuetsu Se11u'' by editing and revising it under the name "Kyōzan Jin Momoki."
