Santō Kyōzan's representative works include ''Fukushū Imoseyama Monogatari'' (''The Tale of Vengeance at Imoseyama,'' 1807) and ''Mukashi Moyō Musume Hyōbanki'' (''Old Patterns of Maidenly Fame,'' 1835).<ref>{{kotobank|Mukashi Moyō Musume Hyōbanki|デジタル大辞泉の解説}}</ref><ref>Takagi Gen (trans.), illustrated by {{ill|Utagawa Kunisada|ja|歌川国貞|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Utagawa Kunisada|qq=}}, {{ill|Utagawa Kunisada III|ja|歌川国貞 (3代目)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Utagawa Kunisada III|qq=}}, {{ill|Utagawa Kuniteru II|ja|歌川国輝 (2代目)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Utagawa Kuniteru II|qq=}}, {{ill|Utagawa Yoshitsuna|ja|歌川芳綱|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Utagawa Yoshitsuna|qq=}}, and {{ill|Utagawa Kuniyoshi|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Utagawa Kuniyoshi|qq=}}. ''Santō Kyōzan: Tales of Eccentric Antiquity'' (Edo Strange Tales and Curiosities Anthology). 2003. ISBN: 978-4336042743.</ref> His lifelong projects include ''Ōmisoka Akebono Zōshi'' (''New Year's Eve Dawn Tales,'' begun in Tenpō 10 (1839)) and ''Oborozuki Neko Kusazōshi'' (''Oborozuki's Cat Tales,'' 1842–1849), illustrated by Utagawa Kuniyoshi.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Oborozuki Neko Kusazōshi Vol. 7, 28 volumes|NCID=BB04697476|qq=draft}}. In 2013, translated and republished as ''The Great Adventures of Okoma: Tales of Oborozuki’s Cat'' by Kaneko Nobuhisa. ISBN: 978-4756244291.</ref> He also wrote ''Kyōkusō Nyōbō Kageki'' (''Female Models for Moral Instruction,'' Kōka 3 (1846)), which incorporated moral lessons targeted at women and girls. His essay ''Rekisei Jōsōkō'' (''An Examination of Female Dress Across the Ages,'' Kōka 4 (1847)) remains a valuable historical source on Edo-period customs.
